Total Cost: n^2 + 15n + 3
Runtime: O(n^2)

The vector has a worst-case loading runtime of O(n^2). Reading the file and creating course objects are linear operations, but validating prerequisites requires searching through the temporary courseNumbers vector. Since that search can take O(n) time and can happen for up to n courses, the worst-case cost becomes O(n^2).
The memory for the vector is O(n) because one course object is stored for each course. Additional temporary vectors, such as fileLines and courseNumbers, also require O(n) memory.
Advantages of the vector:
The vector is simple to understand and easy to implement. It stores course objects in a straightforward list and uses memory efficiently. It is also easy to sort the vector alphanumerically by course number before printing the course list.
Disadvantages of the vector:
Searching for a specific course requires scanning through the vector, which takes O(n) time. Printing an ordered course list requires sorting the vector first, which takes O(n log n). The vector is simple, but it is not the fastest structure for repeated course lookups.

