Runtime: O(n^2)
The hash table has a worst-case loading runtime of O(n^2). Since there are n courses, worst-case insertion can add another O(n^2). However, in the average case, hash table insertion is usually O(1), which makes the hash table very efficient for loading and searching when collisions are handled well.
The memory for the hash table is O(n). It stores one course object per course, but it also requires extra memory for buckets or table slots. Temporary storage for fileLines and courseNumbers also requires O(n). Overall memory use is still O(n), but with more overhead than a vector.
Advantages of the hash table:
The hash table is very fast for searching when it performs well. Looking up a specific course by course number is O(1) on average. This makes it a strong choice for the advisor requirement of printing one specific course and its prerequisites.
Disadvantages of the hash table:
A hash table does not naturally store data in sorted order. To print all courses in alphanumeric order, the program would need to copy the hash table contents into another structure and sort them, which takes O(n log n). Hash tables can also have collision issues, which can reduce performance in the worst case.

