The binary search tree has a worst-case loading runtime of O(n^2). Reading the file and creating the course objects are linear operations, but prerequisite validation can take O(n^2). Inserting into a binary search tree can also take O(n) per course in the worst case if the tree becomes unbalanced. Such as when course numbers are inserted in already sorted order. Since there are n courses, the worst-case insertion cost is O(n^2). In the average case, insertion into a reasonably balanced tree is O(log n), which would make the insertion portion O(n log n).
The memory for the binary search tree is O(n). Each course is stored in one tree node. Each node also stores references to a left child and a right child, so the tree has more pointer overhead than a vector. However, overall memory growth is still linear.
Advantages of the binary search tree:
The binary search tree is the best structure for printing courses in alphanumeric order because an in-order traversal prints the course numbers from lowest to highest without needing a separate sorting step. Searching for a specific course is also efficient on average, with O(log n) search time if the tree is reasonably balanced.
Disadvantages of the binary search tree:
The main disadvantage is that a regular binary search tree can become unbalanced. If the courses are inserted in sorted order, the tree can behave like a linked list, causing search and insertion to degrade to O(n). It is also more complex to implement than a vector or hash table.

Comparison of Advisor Requirements
Requirement 1: Print all courses in alphanumeric order
Vector:
The vector must be sorted before printing. Sorting takes O(n log n), and printing takes O(n). Total runtime is O(n log n).
Hash Table:
The hash table does not store courses in sorted order. The program must copy the courses into another structure and sort them. This also takes O(n log n).
Binary Search Tree:
The binary search tree can print the courses in sorted order using in-order traversal. This takes O(n), which is better than sorting a vector or hash table every time the list is printed.
Requirement 2: Print one course title and prerequisites
Vector:
Searching for a course in a vector takes O(n) because the program may need to scan every course.
Hash Table:
Searching for a course in a hash table takes O(1) on average, making it the fastest option for individual course lookup. In the worst case, due to collisions, it can degrade to O(n).
Binary Search Tree:
Searching for a course in a binary search tree takes O(log n) on average if the tree is balanced. In the worst case, if the tree is unbalanced, searching can degrade to O(n).

Recommendation
I recommend using the binary search tree for the ABCU advising program. Although the worst-case loading time can be O(n^2) if the tree becomes unbalanced, the binary search tree best supports the advisor's requirement to print all courses in alphanumeric order. Since an in-order traversal prints the courses from lowest to highest course number, the program can display the sorted course list in O(n) time without performing a separate sort.
The hash table is very strong for quickly finding one course because it provides O(1) average lookup time. However, it does not naturally keep courses sorted, so printing the full course list requires copying and sorting the data. The vector is the simplest structure, but it requires linear searching for individual courses and sorting for the full course list. The binary search tree provides the best balance between the two major requirements: printing all courses in sorted order and finding an individual course efficiently. For this reason, I would use the binary search tree in the final Project One code.
